# Spec Type Selection Guide

## Feature Specs (`specs/feature/`)

**Use when:**
- Adding new functionality to existing systems
- Building new capabilities or user-facing features
- Implementing significant enhancements
- Developing new APIs, interfaces, or integrations

**Examples:**
- Adding user authentication
- Implementing reporting dashboard
- Building REST API
- Adding real-time notifications

## Bug Specs (`specs/bug/`)

**Use when:**
- Fixing reported defects or issues
- Resolving incorrect behavior
- Addressing production incidents
- Fixing edge cases or error conditions

**Examples:**
- Fixing crashes on invalid input
- Resolving authentication failures
- Correcting calculation errors
- Fixing memory leaks

## Chore Specs (`specs/chore/`)

**Use when:**
- Setting up infrastructure or tooling
- Refactoring without changing functionality
- Updating dependencies or configuration
- Implementing build, deployment, CI/CD improvements
- Organizing documentation or project structure

**Examples:**
- Setting up meta-repository structure
- Configuring CI/CD pipelines
- Upgrading dependencies
- Implementing linting standards

## Design Specs (`specs/design/`)

**Use when:**
- Exploring different architectural approaches
- Prototyping new concepts
- Evaluating technical feasibility
- Creating proof-of-concepts
- Researching and comparing solution options

**Examples:**
- Evaluating state management approaches
- Prototyping UI component library
- Exploring microservices vs monolithic
- Designing API contracts
- Comparing database options

## Planning Specs (`specs/planning/`)

**Use when:**
- Conducting research or discovery work
- Planning complex multi-phase initiatives
- Analyzing requirements for future work
- Evaluating technical debt
- Creating roadmaps or strategic plans

**Examples:**
- Researching third-party service options
- Planning major system migration
- Analyzing performance bottlenecks
- Creating technical roadmap
- Evaluating architectural changes
